The paper focuses on optimization problems on social networks, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. The use of algorithms and optimization also suggests that it could belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The study of network topology and visibility could also place it in the cs.SOC (Social and Economic Networks) sub-category. The consideration of network coverage problems and the ability to interact strategically with the network could suggest the cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) sub-category. Finally, the use of randomized algorithms and optimization could also suggest the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category.
